Form.html#create.title: create( display )  {*}
Form.html#create.name: create
Form.html#create.description: Create a new form instance provided the display of the form.

Form.html#setDisplay.title: setDisplay( display )  {Promise.<T>}
Form.html#setDisplay.name: setDisplay
Form.html#setDisplay.description: Changes the display of the form.

Form.html#.embed.title: <static> embed( embed, options )
Form.html#.embed.name: embed
Form.html#.embed.description: Embeds a form into a website. This method is used to automatically include the Form.io styles into the header as well as inject the DOM element used to contain the form embedded into a page. Form.embed({ src: 'https://examples.form.io/example', class: 'formio-form-wrapper' }).then((instance) => { instance.on('change', (change) => { console.log('The form has changed!', change); }); });

Form.html#build.title: build()  {Promise.<(Webform|PDF|Wizard)>}
Form.html#build.name: build
Form.html#build.description: Build a new form. This is a method that performs all three phases of form creation. Render - Which takes the template of the form to create an HTML string of the form. Inject - Which takes the HTML string and then sets the contents of the DOM element with that string. Attach - Which will attach all event listeners, load references, and perform logic on the rendered DOM elements. const wizard = new Form(document.getElementById('formio'), 'https://examples.form.io/wizard'); wizard.ready.then(() => { wizard.build().then((instance) => { // Will return a Wizard instance since the form.display is set to "wizard" console.log(instance); }); });

Form.html#render.title: render()  {Promise.<string>}
Form.html#render.name: render
Form.html#render.description: Generates an HTML string representation of the form that will be rendered within the application.

Formio.html#.clearCache.title: <static> clearCache()
Formio.html#.clearCache.name: clearCache
Formio.html#.clearCache.summary: Clears the runtime internal API cache.
Formio.html#.clearCache.description: By default, the Formio class will cache all API requests in memory so that any subsequent requests using GET method will return the cached results as long as the API URl is the same as what was cached previously. This cache can be cleared using this method as follows. Formio.clearCache(); Or, if you just wish to clear a single request, then the Formio.request#options.ignoreCache option can be provided when making an API request as follows. Formio.loadForm({}, { ignoreCache: true }).then((form) => { console.log(form); }); Both of the following will ensure that a new request is made to the API server and that the results will not be from the cached result.

Formio.html#.accessInfo.description: This is useful for an application to determine the UI for a specific user to identify which forms they have access to submit or read.

Formio.html#.pageQuery.name: pageQuery
Formio.html#.pageQuery.summary: Returns the query passed to a page in JSON object format.
Formio.html#.pageQuery.description: For example, lets say you visit your application using the url as follows. https://yourapplication.com/?token=23423423423&username=Joe The following code will provide your application with the following. const query Formio.pageQuery(); console.log(query.token); // Will print 23423423423 console.log(query.username); // Will print Joe

Formio.html#.oAuthCurrentUser.name: oAuthCurrentUser
Formio.html#.oAuthCurrentUser.summary: Much like Formio.currentUser, but instead automatically injects the Bearer tokens into the headers to perform a Token swap of the OAuth token which will then return the JWT token for that user.

Formio.html#.samlInit.title: <static> samlInit( options )  {boolean|Promise.<Object>|void}
Formio.html#.samlInit.name: samlInit
Formio.html#.samlInit.description: Typically, you would use the Formio.ssoInit method to perform this function since this method is an alias for the following. Formio.samlInit(); Formio.ssoInit('saml'); // This is the exact same thing as calling Formio.samlInit This method will return false if the process is just starting. The code below is a typical block of code that is used to automatically trigger the SAML authentication process within your application using a Button component. if (Formio.pageQuery().saml) { const sso = Formio.samlInit(); if (sso) { sso.then((user) => { // The SSO user is now loaded! console.log(user); }); } } You can then place the following code withiin the "Custom" action of a Button component on your form. Formio.samlInit(); Now when you click on this button, it will start the handshake process with SAML, and once it returns, will pass a "saml" query parameter back to your application which will execute the code to load the current user from SAML.

Formio.html#.oktaInit.title: <static> oktaInit( options )  {Promise.<Object>}
Formio.html#.oktaInit.name: oktaInit
Formio.html#.oktaInit.summary: Perform an Okta Authentication process using the Okta SDK.
Formio.html#.oktaInit.description: This method does require that you first include the Okta JavaScript SDK within your application as follows. First you need to include the Okta Authentication script. <script src="https://ok1static.oktacdn.com/assets/js/sdk/okta-auth-js/2.0.1/okta-auth-js.min.js" type="text/javascript"></script> Then you can call this method as follows. Formio.oktaInit();

Formio.html#.ssoInit.name: ssoInit
Formio.html#.ssoInit.summary: A common static method to trigger any SSO processes. This method is really just an alias for other static methods.

Formio.html#.requireLibrary.title: <static> requireLibrary( name, property, src, polling )  {Promise.<object>}
Formio.html#.requireLibrary.name: requireLibrary
Formio.html#.requireLibrary.summary: Lazy load a remote library dependency.
Formio.html#.requireLibrary.description: This is useful for components that wish to lazy load a required library by adding that library to the section of the HTML webpage, and then provide a promise that will resolve when the library becomes available for use.

Formio.html#.libraryReady.title: <static> libraryReady( name )  {Promise.<object>}
Formio.html#.libraryReady.name: libraryReady
Formio.html#.libraryReady.summary: Determines if a lazy loaded library is ready to be used.
Formio.html#.libraryReady.description: Example: Let's assume that the example provided at Formio.requireLibrary was used elsewhere in your application. You could now use the following within a separate place that will also resolve once the library is ready to be used. Formio.libraryReady('googleMaps').then(() => { // Once the promise resolves, the following can now be used within your application. const map = new google.maps.Map(document.getElementById("map"), {...}); });
